The noun is derived from {{inh|en|enm|orient}}, {{m|enm|oriente}}, {{m|enm|oryent}}, {{m|enm|oryente}}, {{m|enm|oryentte|t=the east direction; eastern horizon or sky; eastern regions of the world, Asia, Orient; eastern edge of the world}},<ref>{{R:MED Online|entry=orient(e|pos=n|id=MED30896|accessdate=11 June 2019}}</ref> borrowed from {{der|en|xno|orient}}, {{m|fro|oriente}}, and {{der|en|fro|orient|t=east direction; Asia, Orient}} (modern {{cog|fr|orient}}), or directly from its {{glossary|etymon}} {{der|en|la|oriēns|t=the east; daybreak, dawn; sunrise; (''participle'') rising; appearing; originating}}, {{glossary|present}} {{glossary|active}} {{glossary|participle}} of {{m|la|orior|t=to get up, rise; to appear, become visible; to be born, come to exist, originate}}, from {{der|en|ine-pro|*h₃er-|t=to move, stir; to rise, spring}}.<ref>Compare {{R:OED Online|pos=n.'' and ''adj|id=132525|date=September 2004|nodot=yes}}; {{R:Lexico}}</ref>

The adjective is derived from {{inh|en|enm|orient|t=eastern; from Asia or the Orient; brilliant, shining (characteristic of jewels from the Orient)}}, from {{inh|en|enm|orient|pos=noun}}; ''see above''.<ref>{{R:MED Online|pos=adj|id=MED30893|accessdate=11 June 2019}}</ref>

The verb is derived from {{der|en|fr|orienter|t=to orientate; to guide; to set to north}} from {{der|en|fr|orient|pos=noun}} (''see above'') + {{m|fr|-er|pos=''suffix forming infinitives of first-conjugation verbs''}}.<ref>{{R:OED Online|pos=v|id=132526|date=September 2004}}</ref>

